│ value per predecessor.\n\n2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log: The log shows the PHI node `%use = phi i64 [ %start2, %for.body ]` in the exit block. After vectorization, the exit block has two predecessors: `for.body` │
│ and `middle.block`, but the PHI node still only has one incoming value.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis: The issue is in the `collectUsersInExitBlock` function (lines 8654-8674). It collects PHI nodes in the exit │
│ block that need to be fixed, but it only looks at the incoming value from the exiting block (`ExitingBB`). When a PHI node has a constant value (like `%start2`), the function should handle it specially. The │
│ PHI node `%use` has a constant value `%start2` from the `for.body` block. After vectorization, this PHI node needs to be updated to have incoming values from both `for.body` and `middle.block`.\n\nLooking   │
│ at the code, `collectUsersInExitBlock` collects PHI nodes and creates `ExitingValuesToFix`. Then `addUsersInExitBlock` creates extracts and live-outs for them. However, for PHI nodes with constant values,   │
│ the code at line 8700-8702 handles them by passing live-in values directly through to the live-out. But this doesn't update the PHI node itself in the IR.\n\nThe real issue is that when a PHI node has a     │
│ constant incoming value, it should be replaced entirely (not just have a live-out added). The PHI node should be removed and replaced with the constant value, or updated to have incoming values from all     │
│ predecessors.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s): The fix should be in `collectUsersInExitBlock` to skip PHI nodes that have constant values (i.e., `ExitPhi.hasConstantValue()` returns non-null). These PHI nodes  │
│ don't need to be fixed because they can be replaced with their constant value. Alternatively, we need to handle them specially in the transformation phase.\n\nLooking at line 8700-8702 in                    │
│ `addUsersInExitBlock`:\n```cpp\nif (V->isLiveIn()) {\n  Plan.addLiveOut(ExitPhi, V);\n  continue;\n}\n```\nThis handles live-in values but doesn't remove or update the PHI node. The PHI node remains in the  │
│ IR with only one incoming value.\n\nWe should modify `collectUsersInExitBlock` to skip PHI nodes that have constant values:\n\n```cpp\nfor (PHINode &ExitPhi : ExitBB->phis()) {\n  // Skip PHI nodes with     │
│ constant values - they don't need fixing\n  if (ExitPhi.hasConstantValue())\n    continue;\n  \n  Value *IncomingValue = ExitPhi.getIncomingValueForBlock(ExitingBB);\n  // ... rest of the code\n}\n```\n\n5. │
│ Conclusion: The fix is to skip PHI nodes with constant values in `collectUsersInExitBlock` because they don't need to be fixed - they can be replaced with their constant value. This prevents the invalid PHI │
│ node from being left in the IR after vectorization."})                                                                                                                                                         │
